I'm working on a web project and need to optimize some of our JavaScript functions for better performance. I'd like to start with debouncing our search function which is currently called 'searchQuery' and set the delay to 300 milliseconds. If this works well, I then want to throttle a function called 'updateResults', setting the throttle time to 200 milliseconds, and make sure it executes at the beginning of the throttle period. Let's also set a max wait time of 1000 milliseconds for it.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
[debounceHandler(func="searchQuery", wait=300, options={"leading": false, "trailing": true})]
<|end|>
<|tool|>
[{"name": "debounceHandler", "results": {"debouncedFunc": "debouncedSearchQuery"}}]
<|end|>
<|asst|>
[throttleHandler(func="updateResults", wait=200, options={"leading": true, "trailing": false, "maxWait": 1000})]
<|end|>
<|tool|>
[{"name": "throttleHandler", "results": {"throttledFunc": "throttledUpdateResults"}}]
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Your 'searchQuery' function has been successfully debounced with a delay of 300 milliseconds. The new debounced function is named 'debouncedSearchQuery'. Additionally, I've created a throttled version of 'updateResults', which executes at the beginning of the throttle period with a throttle time of 200 milliseconds and a maximum wait time of 1000 milliseconds. The result is 'throttledUpdateResults'.
<|end|>


